I'm not going to get into the idea of not paying "regular" speakers but paying 5-6 figures for the keynotes.

The keynoters are not who creates value for an event and paying some speakers but not others is even less equitable than paying none of them.

Could you imagine telling an event space that you don't need to pay them because your event is bringing exposure to the location?

Or the event planner that they can just add the event to their portfolio?

Now why are things different for speakers?

A common response as to why events don't pay speakers is budget.

But...these people are working at your event.

Everyone working your event should be compensated for their labor.

If you can't afford to pay people working with you, maybe you can't afford the event.

The traits of ADHD are so normal that almost everyone experiences them at some point.

So why distance ADHD symptoms from the human experience by fictionalizing them?

The superpower narrative around ADHD symptoms just isn't necessary. 

Superhumans aren't real.

My ADHD and I very much are.

The superpower narrative also easily slides into "it's not that bad" narratives, which are then often used to deny people accommodations in school, work, etc.

After all, why would someone with superpowers need help?!

If it does for you, honestly I'm jealous.

But for me, the negatives always outweigh the positives. By a lot.

There are parts of ADHD that are positives to me, like creativity and the ability to entertain myself, but even those aren't so glamorous that the word "superpower" feels anything like an accurate description.

Honestly, the idea of things like hyperfocus being superpowers has just never resonated with my experience.

More often than not, they're a negative to my experience.

So forcing myself to reframe that just wouldn't be natural or authentic coping mechanism for me.

There are 3 main reasons I don't call my ADHD a superpower:

1. It minimizes a big part of the experience
2. It's the same mindset often used to deny accommodations
3. It dehumanizes human traits

I don't like calling my ADHD (or any of my disabilities) a superpower.

Here's why...

(with the caveat that these are obviously just my own opinions and you're free to disagree with them)

That doesn't even mean I'm not posting on Instagram at all, or don't plan to publish any videos.

But they're pretty far down on the list of marketing priorities.

And instead, I'm focusing on boring blog posts & emails.

By accidentally letting go of things like Instagram and YouTube last year, I saw how unnecessary they were to doubling my email list and growing organic traffic to 50k users/year.

So this year I'm letting them go intentionally.

And whenever I try to add on a new component too soon, it messes with the workflows of what's already working.

But the beauty of that is that it let me more clearly see how well things like SEO and lead magnets work even when I'm not actively working on them.

Looking back on the past few years, I rushed to diversify marketing channels too soon.

An example is how, as soon as I got into a groove of blogging weekly a few years ago...

Instead of doubling down on it & letting it work, I launched a YouTube channel.

Fellow disabled, chronically ill, neurodivergent, and mentally ill folks: does this misfit concept resonate with you as much as it does with me?

Like you've been walking around in a world that just didn't fit?

From the book:

"The condition of disability is present whenever a body finds itself in what scholar Rosemarie Garland-Thomson has called a pointed “misfit” relationship with the world—not the melodrama of a tragedy to overcome, not merely a "defect" of the flesh, but a misfit.”

So much of our struggles come from having to interact with the world the way a square peg interacts with a round hole. 

There's nothing wrong with or broken about the peg, the conditions around it just don't fit.

This is how disability scholar Rosemarie Garland-Thomson describes how non-normative bodies and brains interact with our world.

It's a mismatched relationship, not a personal failing.

One of my favorite books of 2021 was What Can a Body Do?, about how disabled bodies meet the built world.

In it, I learned about the concept of "misfit bodies," which I absolutely love.

6. Social media boundaries

It’s been something I’ve been experimenting with and writing about for years, but I finally feel like I’m in a good place with social media.

(Most days.)

At this point, I spend less than half an hour a day total on social media.

5. Starting to drive again

I hadn’t driven consistently since I lived in Delaware in 2015, and at all since I’d gotten really sick.

Between my anxiety getting so bad and having such little energy, it just never felt safe.

It's been amazing to regain some independence.

4. Consistent therapy

I started with a new virtual therapy service, with weekly calls & medication management.

This is the most consistently I’ve gone to therapy since college, and I’ve made a ton of progress on some mental health and self-worth issues as a result. 🎉

3. Embracing biphasic sleep

When the pandemic started making my nighttime sleep even worse than usual, I fully embraced biphasic sleep. 

Planning for a nap every day, building it into my schedule, and not feeling mad or guilty if I only get a few hours during my “first sleep.”

2. Launching a signature content strategy course

The reason I slowed down client work was so I could put more energy & focus into preselling and developing the curriculum for a new course about the content remix method.

The presale made $7k in a few weeks, my best launch yet.

1. Focusing on my own brands

2021 was the first year that product sales from both Work Brighter and https://t.co/01l2irzBah total more than client work.

I only took on, like, 3 writing projects and 2 calls.

✨ Focusing on my own brands

But for a while now, I've been working on...let's call them micro-habits...to change this:

- Daily content consumption & note making
- Building an evergreen note library
- Assembling long-form pieces from these short-form components

My content calendar and workflow still started with a long-form piece of content, which I publish 1-2 pieces of per week.

And I still tried to write them each in one sitting.

Key word being tried...

My health, schedule, and habits have changed a lot over the past few years though.

Yet I hadn't updated my content workflow to match.

That worked fine when I had more energy, was healthier, and had a more structured schedule.

When I could sit down and write a 2,000-word blog post in one sitting, multiple times per week, and remix the content for other channels in between.

Oh, those were the days. 😬

For the past 10 years, my approach to content remixing around a topic has been:

📝 Decide on the topic and outline
📝 Create the whole piece of long-form content
📝 Break it down into smaller parts to remix

It was top-down and sprint-focused.

That's NOT going to change, but the way I create and work with that long-form content is.

Here's how:

If you know my work, you know I'm a long-form content gal.

I rarely publish a blog post less than 1,000 words long, regularly run out of room in single tweets (hi hello), and am intimately familiar with the character limit on Instagram captions.

Not to be dramatic or anything, but I think I've burned down my whole content creation workflow and started building a new one. 😶

It's been a long time coming, a long time of trying, and I think it's finally starting to work.

Here's the deal...

Especially if you deal with chronic illness, mental illness, and neurodivergence, talking about sleep can be a LOT more complicated.

Here are some things I want you to consider: https://t.co/e96ljeP0lb

Is it really revenge bedtime procrastination, or are you just on the wrong sleep schedule for your body? 🤔

Revenge bedtime procrastination has gone viral, and don't get me wrong: I get it.

It's relatable & fun to joke about.

But are you taking your sleep problems seriously?

That 2 hours sounds like a lot of time for journaling...

AND IT IS!

But it's also time spent on almost *every* other area of my work.

That 2 hours is really:

- 30 min meeting
- 30 min planning
- 30 min thinking
- 30 min writing

A pretty productive morning, yes?

And that planning includes content planning! 📝

On days that I'm starting a new long-form piece of content, I use my morning pages to think out what it needs to accomplish, then transfer it into the official outline and take it from there.

Journaling is also like planning.

Since I spend the time thinking out what I need to do, how, and what priority each item is, my "official" planning process takes less time.

All the hard stuff's figured out, I'm just entering it into my calendar. 📅

Since I work alone, journaling is like my daily meeting block.

So you could probably count at least 30 minutes of my daily journaling time as my businesses' "team meetings" 🤣

(Our team members don' t always get along, so things can get chaotic 🙃)

I KNOW all that stuff would have taken so much longer without this habit.

And journaling isn't just thinking time, it's also meeting time and planning time. 📅

Since starting morning pages, I have:

- launched and started the course that'd been in my head for *years*
- figured out the new @workbrighterco positioning I struggled with for months
- made a huge aha about its future business model

Journaling is my thinking time. 🧠

That means that for 2 hours a day, I'm now more or less alone with my thoughts. 

And as a creative and entrepreneur, that has already had SO MANY noticeable benefits.

When i first saw that number in my time tracker, I *immediately* felt guilty. 🙈

"WHAT A WASTE OF TIME! THAT'S YOUR WHOLE MORNING" - my inner critic

But since then, I've realized a few things...

Earlier this year i started doing morning pages on top of the 10-minute daily review i do before bed...

and...

I just realized I'm now journaling for almost 2 HOURS a day  🤯
reminder: most brains can't handle more than 4 hours per day of deep, focused work.

@_Wanderwell_ like i couldn't give a shit about this inclusivity award everyone seems to be vying for these days. im trying to keep my people alive 2 years into an ongoing, constant attack on our humanity.

I know these are all ideal scenarios and reality is not that.

I didn't get to follow the career transition plan I originally made when I decided to start my business.

But I also think we need to stop glorifying full-time entrepreneurship & talk about the different options.

And finally, if you want to learn how to run a business, work at a startup.

I 100% believe it gave me a huge head start when I started my business. And that's part of why I decided to work at one before taking my own projects full-time.

If side hustling on the side of a full-time job isn't for you, consider if it's possible to take a "bridge job:" a part-time job that can help pay bills while you build your business.

That way you can make business decisions based on long-term vision instead of paying your rent.

This is what I wish I could have done! 

Instead of freelancing full-time with my template shop as essentially a side hustle, I could have built that shop while still working a job with PTO and health insurance.

If you want to start a product-based business, quitting employment cold turkey → starting a service-based business → transitioning services to products is a roundabout way to get there.

The simpler option is to jump straight to the biz model you want, but as a side hustle.

The "start with services" advice comes from the assumption that money's the only thing that matters.

And if you just leap into full-time entrepreneurship with no transition, that will be true.

But we can try (key word being try) to avoid that.

In my last thread, I shared why I disagree with the advice that services are the easiest way to start an entrepreneurial journey. (https://t.co/b3NF7CM15P)

So what are the options instead?

1. Product-based side hustle
2. Part-time bridge job
3. Work at a startup

#ship30for30

So next time someone tells you services are simple or easy, remember to question what part they play in your actual goals.

And as I'm doing that, I can help but get angry at how much time & energy it feels like I wasted building a totally different audience base for totally different offers serving totally different needs.

It hindered my long-term goals more than helped them.

Over the past year and a half, I finally figured my way out of the services handcuffs.

I stopped working with all but 2 clients, and only book 1 project a month (previously it was ~10).

The financial hit has been REAL.

But I'm finally building the business I really want.

The idea we're sold is "booking ourselves out" with client work then using that experience & income to create a course.

But too many of us are using that income to live and survive on.

Clearing our client roster/calendar to work on products impacts that.
There are products that I wanted to build for years, like my upcoming content marketing course, that I was never able to work on because after serving my clients, I had nothing left for me.

This happens for 2 main reasons:

1. Services are time- and energy-intensive, so you have little capacity left to work on your "main" idea

2. They require systems and boundaries newer entrepreneurs are less likely to have, which can become golden handcuffs & exacerbate burnout

Now, for the problems with the "start with services" approach.

The umbrella problem with it is that it's taking you down a path that's not the path your goal is on. 

And all the time you spend going down it can take you further away from your real goal.

First, a caveat: this is specific to the advice that you should start with services no matter what, regardless of your long-term business goals.

If those long-term goals ARE related to being a service provider, sweet!

The problem is how often it's not.

One of the MOST common pieces of advice for new entrepreneurs is to "start with services."

Well, I did, and it's one of the things I regret most about the early days of my business. 😬

So here's when and why you SHOULDN'T follow that advice.

It became impossible to improve my mental health and improve my business at the same time, and I had to make a choice.

So I chose my mental health and changed my business.

The industry being driven by ableism did not make it easy to gain authority and respect as someone who doesn't know how to be quiet about my disabilities anymore.

Forget getting people to see me as an expert, I was having trouble getting them to see me as human.

What I didn't see at the time, was that all the values and beliefs that made the tech space toxic for me, were just as prevalent in the entrepreneurship space.

Maybe even more so.

I was starting this business at the same time that I was in serious treatment for a lot of mental and physical illness and coming to terms with my internalized ableism. 

I was starting to see how Hustle Culture amplified it, which was part of why I left in-house work in tech.

It seemed to make sense, since I like relating to my customers and lots of them needed help with content marketing.

What I didn't take into account was the values and identity part of things.

It's something we need to consider as well, and I learned that the hard way.

When I first went full-time in my business, I started shifting my brand to focus more on serving other entrepreneurs and small business owners.

We talk a lot about product/market fit.

Less frequently, we talk about product/founder fit.

But what about founder/market fit?
